d, United Kingdom":"Cranbrook, Kent, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bigge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Bigg  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bigg","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>bigge</i> ‘large, strong, stout’, presumably a descriptive nickname for a large, strong person.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>big</i> ‘building’, a derivative of Middle English <i>biggen</i> (Old Norse <i>byggja</i>) ‘to build’.","In some cases possibly also an Americanized form of German   Bick   or of some other similar (like-sounding) name from continental Europe (compare   Big   2)."]}]},{"name":"Lord","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably a respelling of   Laura  , that coincides in form with the German spelling of the same name and also with the medieval English given name."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lord Roger Bigge was born in 1395, in Benenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Thomas John Bigge and Gese von Negendank. He married Joan Kent of Plantagenent about 1420, in Benenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in June 1474, in his hometown, at the age of 79."},"et":{"1395–Jun 1474":"1395–juuni 1474","1395–1474":"1395–1474","1406–1443":"1406–1443","1400–1472":"1400–1472","1420–1472":"1420–1472","1420–1488":"1420–1488","1424–1474":"1424–1474","1378–1452":"1378–1452","–Female":"Surnud","Jun 1474":"juuni 1474","1 April 1424":"1. aprill 1424","1395":"1395","1472":"1472","June 1472":"juuni 1472","1424":"1424","1378":"1378","1488":"1488","1400":"1400","1443":"1443","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1474":"1474","before 1395":"enne 1395","about 1420":"umbes 1420","1406":"1406","Marden, Kent, England":"Marden, Kent, England","Benenden, Kent, England":"Benenden, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cranbrook, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Cranbrook, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1395–Jun 1474":"1395–kesäkuu 1474","1395–1474":"1395–1474","1406–1443":"1406–1443","1400–1472":"1400–1472","1420–1472":"1420–1472","1420–1488":"1420–1488","1424–1474":"1424–1474","1378–1452":"1378–1452","–Female":"Kuollut","Jun 1474":"kesäkuu 1474","1 April 1424":"1. huhtikuuta 1424","1395":"1395","1472":"1472","June 1472":"kesäkuu 1472","1424":"1424","1378":"1378","1488":"1488","1400":"1400","1443":"1443","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1474":"1474","before 1395":"ennen vuotta 1395","about 1420":"noin 1420","1406":"1406","Marden, Kent, England":"Marden, Kent, England","Benenden, Kent, England":"Benenden, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cranbrook, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Cranbrook, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1395–J